Behaviour of Linearly and non-linearly separable data¶

The algorithm would converge to a solution within the maximum number of epochs and print the solution in case of linearly separable data. In the case of non-linearly separable data, the algorithm cannot get the correct decision boundary and would run till the maximum number of attempts it is allowed as written in the algorithmm.

Dependence on the inital weights:¶

The decision boundary is very much dependent on the initial values Since the decision boundary is plotted based on the weights and bias, different weights would result in a different boundary being drawn. Also depending on the dataset present, the algorithm would converge in less/more steps than when the weights are initialized to 0. Some times it would not even converge. The update step of the algorithm is dependent on the previous values of the weights which makes the updatation of weights by a differnet value with different initializations.

SVM vs Perceptron:¶

The SVM algorithm helps in obtaining a decision boundary that maximizes the distance between the points and the boundary.Whereas in the case of the perceptron algorithm, it stops when all the points are classified correctly. Also, one more main difference between them is that the perceptron algorithm could be used for online training whereas the SVM is trained only once.

Logistic Regression vs Perceptron:¶

The logistic regression algorithm is the same as the perceptron algorithm with sigmoid activation function. Logistic regression is a probablistic model that gives the value betweeen 0 and 1. In the case of a normal perceptron algorithm, we have a step function which acts a threshold and any output greater than the threshold is passed through to the output and anything less than that threshold is not allowed to pass.

Plotting the decion boundary of a linearly separable dataset¶

In [4]:
def plotStageBoundary(X,y,weight,bias,typeLin):
    y[y==-1]=0
    df = pd.DataFrame(dict(x=X[:,0], y=X[:,1], label=y))
    colors = {0:'red', 1:'blue'}      
    for i in range(len(df)):
        plt.scatter(df["x"][i], df["y"][i], c=colors[df["label"][i]])
    if(typeLin=="Linear"):
        x_space = np.linspace(-10,10,100)
    if(typeLin=="NonLinear"):
        x_space = np.linspace(-1,2,10)
    y_space =-((weight[0]/weight[1])*x_space) -(bias/weight[1])
    plt.plot(x_space, y_space, '-')
    plt.show()
    y[y==0]=-1

Make the linearly separabel dataset with make_blobs with random variable as 2,20¶

In [5]:
def MakeDataset(randomVar,typeData):
    if typeData=="Linear":
        X, y = make_blobs(n_samples=200, centers=2, n_features=2,random_state=randomVar)
    elif typeData=="Moon":
        X,y = make_moons(150,2,random_state=2)
    else:
        X,y= make_circles(150,2,random_state=2,noise=0.2)
    df = pd.DataFrame(dict(x=X[:,0], y=X[:,1], label=y))
    colors = {0:'red', 1:'blue'}
    for i in range(len(df)):
        plt.scatter(df["x"][i], df["y"][i], c=colors[df["label"][i]])
    plt.title("The dataset is:")
    plt.show()
    return X,y

Implementation of the perceptron algorithm¶

In [6]:
def perceptronAlgo(X,y,weight,typeLine='NonLinear',randomVar=2,NonLinear_type='circle'):
    bias=0
    count=0
    didItChange=True
    while didItChange is True and count<15:
        didItChange=False
        count=count+1
        for i in range(X.shape[0]):
            x=X[i]
            t=y[i]
            yDash=bias+(np.dot(weight,x))
            if(yDash>0):
                yDash=1.0
            else:
                yDash=-1.0
            if yDash != t:
                didItChange=True
                weight=weight+learning_rate*x*t
                bias=bias+learning_rate*t
        if typeLine == "Linear":
            print("Weight : ", weight," Bias: ",bias)
            plotStageBoundary(X,y,weight,bias,"Linear")
        else:
            print("Weight : ", weight," Bias: ",bias)
            plotStageBoundary(X,y,weight,bias,"NonLinear")
    return weight, bias
